[7/7] He had no one left. It would just be him alone in this place that had already been filled with so much sorrow, now with even more. 

But why does the painting in front of him seem like it is moving?

[6/7] When he goes back to his room, in a fit of grief he lashes out, splashing paint all over his room & onto the painting he had put all his heart into for his mom. A mom that would not be able to see it. He collapses to the floor with tears running down his face,

[5/7] He waits for his mom to come home from work that night, waiting at the front door for hours, but she does not. But when someone is at the door, its not his mom, but a cop. 

She was not coming home anymore.

[4/7] Bob decides to take it home with him to finish what had been started & paint it with the colors it so desperately needed, hoping to show his mother it & finally get her attention. After spending all day & night, putting so much love & effort into it, he completes it.

[3/7] One day while he is out getting more art supplies, he comes across a half finished painting leaned against a trash can, it being of a man about his age leaning against a wall with a vibrant smile & rather stylistic clothes.

[2/7] So basically, when Bob was a teenager he was super into art [but mostly painting] instead of gardening. His mom, Tia, is surprisingly still alive but is a heavy drinker, usually never home, & over all pushes him to the side.
